The duality of stagnation. When something is a focus then eventually it starts to devolve. West anthro artists have been doing it awhile and on top of losing art fundamentals over generations are oversimplifying things for the sake of mass-production and mass-market appeal. Japan has a similar issue with human characters, especially female, and probably to a worse degree, but they never had a big focus on animal anthro characters to the same degree and therefore have to learn everything from scratch without the psuedo-tracing and corner cutting.
There's more to it then that, as homogeneous and uncanny as the anime girls are I'd prefer them to the drawn women of the modern west which have less sex appeal then the women drawn by Michelangelo.

I honestly think the sweet spot is a universe you like but aren't quite into. Keeps you a bit more objective in depicting it. I definitely think I could write better Star Trek fanfiction than I could Firefly fanfiction. Either way, though, writing consistent and believable fanfiction takes a lot of discipline. It isn't really fun to replicate someone else's fictional world, and it takes some critical, attentive reading. You have to replicate what you see, but also understand why it's done that way and what roles the components of the setting play in telling its story so you can be consistent in how you use them yourself. It's kind of a high-research prospect, and it helps a lot to have some academic understanding of why you like the story you're writing fanfiction about, and how to emulate those features.

Fritewag here, dumping my fifty cents on fanfics. Personally? I'm half and half with them.

For one, it's fun to fuck around with characters you like and tell a story in a world you're passionate about. Tigress was the OG furfag waifu for me and I love Chinese history, architecture and culture (From the times before it turned into a communist hellhole, of course), and I think the movies set up a really cool fantastical version of China that begs to be explored further. Writing Lotus is a genuinely enjoyable experience for me, and that's not always the case when it comes to writing stuff.

On the other hand, there are restrictions. You have to work with pre-defined characters, pre-defined locations and so on and so forth. You're only allowed a certain amount of creative freedom.
Someday, after I've finished Lotus, I wanna work on a big fantasy project. Something where I can make my own world and my own characters.

>>40385883
>It also happens to be one of the first places people are compelled to write that isn't for some practical purpose/school/whatever.
It's because it's what people read. Writers go to where audiences are, and there are a lot of TMNT shippers out there who want to read about Master Splinter giving Donatello the ass-pounding of a lifetime. It's not an ideal situation: writing fanfics is like writing with training wheels. All the pieces are there, you just have to tell your own story with them. Good for learning prose, pacing and plot development, but it leaves the character-making and world-building skills a little underdeveloped, hence all the infamous donut steels. It's a good place for an absolute beginner, but a lot of authors grow past the point of needing those training wheels, fully capable of writing something original and fresh, only to realize that writing that special something won't get them anywhere near the amount of audience they had writing Donatello/Master Splinter buttsex.

Now I'm just sumfag, but in my opinion, fanfiction doesn't have to necessarily limit your creative freedom, but the structure of having to work with set characters with set backgrounds and characteristics is a framework that challenges you to be very creative in order to tell a story. I find that readers are willing to suspend their disbelief so long as you guide the characters along to the situation you want to write about while having them act in a manner that is logical and congruent with their background and established personality.

That said, I agree with you that it can stunt the ability of a writer to come up with original characters since you're provided them, but it forces a good writer to fully understand the personalities of those characters in order to portray them in character, doing uncharacteristic things, if that makes sense.
